default3.33
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn digital terrestrial TV (DTT) broadcasting, Ofcom works closely with the BBC, the commercial broadcasters and transmission providers to develop detailed TV frequency plans with the aim of securing specific public policy object
defaultives such as delivering near-universal coverage of public service broadcasting via DTT, as well as providing appropriate spectrum resources for non-public service broadcasting services. DTT frequency planning work is carried out collaboratively by a group 
defaultcomprising all DTT multiplex operators including the BBC. The group is chaired by Ofcom which also retains ultimate responsibility for
default how the spectrum is allocated.
default3.34
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn radio broadcasting, the more diverse range of broadcasters and transmission operators m
defaulteans that the BBC generally develops and manages the allocation of its services within agreed sub-bands or frequency blocks (though in some limited cases commercial and community services make use of frequencies within BBC sub-bands and vice versa), while 
defaultOfcom develops and manages frequency plans for commercial radio broadcasting services. Ofcom does however retain overall responsibility for managing and licensing the use of all of the spectrum used for radio services, 
defaultincluding that used by the BBC.
default3.35
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOfcom
default’s spectrum responsibilities also include securing international frequency co-ordination for terrestrial TV and radio services. International co-ordination rights
default and obligations
default, which 
defaultcover
default the overall spectrum available for the BBC’s services, influence
default the availability and number of terrestrial broadcasting services in the UK. 
default3.36
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn contrast to the commercial broadcasters, the BBC’s services are not 
defaultseparately 
defaultlicensed by Ofcom under the Broadcasting Acts (though there are some limited exceptions to this). Broadcasting Act licences are of fixed duration, with statutory criteria setting out the circumstances under which the licences may be renewed. The Broadcasti
defaultng Act licences issued by Ofcom to the commercial public service broadcasters, multiplex operators and radio services also require adherence 
defaultto certain technical standards.
default3.37
default              
defaultWhile Ofcom has overall responsibility for resolving interference issues betwe
defaulten different wireless services, the BBC has a specific responsibility for investigating suspected cases of interference to domestic TV and radio reception. If the BBC determines that a case of reported interference is being caused by a source such as an un
defaultauthorised radio signal, they may refer the case to Ofcom for further investigation.
defaultCompetition
default&#xa0;
default3.38
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOfcom has a number of roles and duties relating to competition, which broadly 
